"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348753","Home Office","false","2015-06-10","<p>The UK already complies with the vast majority of the articles to the convention including the criminalisation of forced marriage which was one of the pre-requisites of ratification as required by Article 37. Primary legislation will be needed to comply with the remaining extra-territorial jurisdiction provisions in Article 44 of the Convention before it can be ratified. The UK Government is liaising with the devolved administrations about ratification, including any further legislative steps that may be necessary.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-06-10T15:18:42.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348753/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348753/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348753/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348753/answer/previousversion/3586","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-05","Council of Europe Convention on Preventing and Combating Violence against Women and Domestic Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for what reasons the UK has not ratified the 2011 Council of Europe Convention on preventing and combatting violence against women and domestic violence.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","1296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348754","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-10","<p>Part-time season tickets do not currently exist on the rail network. The Government is currently working in partnership with the rail industry to develop both the required infrastructure and the details of exactly how such a product should work for passengers. Until this work is completed, it would not be appropriate or cost-effective to specify part-time season tickets in rail franchises.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-10T13:52:50.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348754/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348754/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348754/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-05","Railways: Season Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will require train operating companies to offer part-time season tickets as a condition of any future franchise awards.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","1318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348755","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-10","<p /> <p>All spending decisions for 16-17 and beyond will be taken as part of the Spending Review, the timetable for which is yet to be finalised.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-06-10T13:40:58.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348755/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348755/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348755/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-05","Further Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether the community learning budget will be ring-fenced for the year 2016-17; and when his Department plans to publish details of that budget.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","1317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348756","Wales Office","false","2015-06-12","<p>In 2013-14, Wales attracted 79 inward investment projects, up from 67 in 2012-13. This was the highest number of inward investment projects for a quarter of a century. Last year the UK Investment Summit in Newport showcased a number of fantastic Welsh businesses and put Wales on the global stage as a great place to invest.</p><p> </p>","Preseli Pembrokeshire","Stephen Crabb",,"2015-06-12T11:27:58.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348756/answer","Biography information for Stephen Crabb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348756/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348756/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-06-05","Foreign Investment in UK: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent estimate he has made of the level of inward investment to Wales; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","1305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348484","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-18","<p>In line with the commitment made by my predecessor to begin to publish annually the performance of departments on their promptness in dealing with QWAs (HL Deb 8 May 2014, col 1575), I have today published data on departmental performance in answering Questions for Written Answer for the 2014/15 session (HLWS39). I am pleased to say that, overall, 91% of Questions for Written Answer were answered within the expected 10 working days in the last session.</p><p><br>I will continue to publish departmental performance data on an annual basis to enable performance to be compared over time. My office will also continue to work with all departments to ensure prompt and comprehensive responses to all Questions for Written Answer.</p>",,"Baroness Stowell of Beeston",,"2015-06-18T16:37:10.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348484/answer","Biography information for Baroness Stowell of Beeston","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348484/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-04","Written Questions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Statement by Lord Bridges of Headley on 3 June (HLWS10), whether they will publish figures on the response rates to questions for written answer during the 2010–15 Parliament along similar lines.","false","Biography information for Lord Jopling",,"Lord Jopling","HL256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348485","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-16","<p>HM Revenue and Customs does not hold the information requested.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-06-16T15:59:29.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348485/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348485/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-04","Minimum Wage","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their estimate of how many people who work 37.5 hours per week or more (1) receive benefits and (2) would receive benefits if the minimum wage were increased to the living wage.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348486","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-16","<p>In order to inform policy making, the government reviews and notes the wider evidence on key international economic questions on an ongoing basis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has a clear mandate to improve Britain’s relationship with the rest of the EU, and to reform the EU so that it creates jobs and increases living standards for all its citizens.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Prime Minister has started to discuss his plans for EU reform and renegotiation with other EU leaders. He has been clear that the plans involve reforming welfare and immigration rules, increasing economic competitiveness and cutting red tape to create jobs and growth for hard working families, and protecting Britain's interests outside the euro.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It also means halting the constant flow of powers to Brussels including by ensuring a stronger role for national Parliaments. The Government will hold an in/out referendum on the UK’s membership of the EU by the end of 2017.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-06-16T16:00:28.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348486/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348486/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-04","UK Membership of EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment, if any, they have made of the economic analysis in the report <i>A Blueprint for Britain: Openness not Isolation</i>.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348487","Department of Health","false","2015-06-18","<p>The Food Standards Agency advises that there are no available comparisons of campylobacter levels between chickens imported into the United Kingdom from outside the European Union and chickens produced in the UK. Chicken imported from outside the EU is not assessed for levels of campylobacter as most chicken imported into the UK is frozen. The European Food Standards Authority has indicated that a greater than 90% risk reduction from campylobacter can be obtained by freezing carcases for two to three weeks.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-06-18T15:50:32.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348487/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348487/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-04","Poultry: Campylobacter","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the level of campylobacter in imported chickens and chicken meat and how it compares to the level found in their recent study of chickens produced in the United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348488","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-09","<p>There are a number of factors that are considered to make marine nuclear propulsion reactors unattractive for landside electricity generation, when compared to a conventional reactor that has been designed specifically for this purpose. All of these are likely to add to the levelised cost of electricity generation from a propulsion reactor used for electricity generation purposes for the national grid, compared to a dedicated land-based reactor. These include the following:</p><p>1) Propulsion reactors are designed for more rapid power cycling than is currently demanded from landside reactors.</p><p>2) The power density of a propulsion reactor is much higher than one would need for a landside power reactor.</p><p>3) The serviceable lifetime for a propulsion reactor is shorter than for a power reactor.</p><p>4) Propulsion reactors are smaller than most reactor designs, varying between a few tens of MW to about 150 MW, resulting in relatively little capacity per unit.</p><p>5) Propulsion reactors’ design would result in the regulatory compliance costs of their landside use for electricity generation being greater than those for a dedicated landside reactor.</p><p>The first two issues add to capital costs of design and construction, the second two to operational costs and the final to regulatory costs.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","HL261","2015-06-09T11:12:44.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348488/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348488/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-04","Nuclear Power","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether there are any reasons why marine nuclear propulsion engines such as the A1B could not be used on land to generate nuclear power if connected in series; and if so, what those reasons are.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348489","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-09","<p>There are a number of factors that are considered to make marine nuclear propulsion reactors unattractive for landside electricity generation, when compared to a conventional reactor that has been designed specifically for this purpose. All of these are likely to add to the levelised cost of electricity generation from a propulsion reactor used for electricity generation purposes for the national grid, compared to a dedicated land-based reactor. These include the following:</p><p>1) Propulsion reactors are designed for more rapid power cycling than is currently demanded from landside reactors.</p><p>2) The power density of a propulsion reactor is much higher than one would need for a landside power reactor.</p><p>3) The serviceable lifetime for a propulsion reactor is shorter than for a power reactor.</p><p>4) Propulsion reactors are smaller than most reactor designs, varying between a few tens of MW to about 150 MW, resulting in relatively little capacity per unit.</p><p>5) Propulsion reactors’ design would result in the regulatory compliance costs of their landside use for electricity generation being greater than those for a dedicated landside reactor.</p><p>The first two issues add to capital costs of design and construction, the second two to operational costs and the final to regulatory costs.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","HL260","2015-06-09T11:12:44.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348489/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348489/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-04","Nuclear Power","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the case for using PWR3 nuclear reactors, mounted on floating barges, as a potential power source for electricity generation in the United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348490","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-17","<p>Since 1 May 2015, the Department for Transport has not taken any specific, additional steps to directly reduce the number of fatalities to cyclists caused by heavy goods vehicles (HGVs).</p><p> </p><p>However, improving road safety including the reduction of cyclists killed or seriously injured on the roads, particularly by HGVs is a subject that we take extremely seriously. The Department continues to work to improve the safety of cyclists and the reduction of cyclist fatalities, through actions including regulations impacting on the design of vehicles, and education campaigns aimed at both drivers and cyclists, for example the THINK! “tips” campaign.</p><p> </p><p>This THINK! campaign uses a series of practical tips to advise and remind both groups of the rules of the road and the positive actions they can take to help reduce cyclist casualties.</p><p> </p><p>The campaign previously ran in Autumn 2013 and Spring 2014 using paid-for roadside advertising in five cities where cycling KSIs are over represented - Cambridge, Bristol, Leeds, Manchester and Birmingham.</p><p> </p><p>THINK! repeated the campaign in these five cities in March 2015, to build on awareness and knowledge of the tips amongst drivers and cyclists. In addition, the campaign was also extended to seven additional cities – Southampton, Newcastle, Portsmouth, Bradford, Kingston upon Hull, Brighton and Hove and Liverpool, these were selected as they also have high levels cyclists being killed or seriously injured (KSIs).</p><p> </p><p>Later this year, the Department will be commencing Section 21 of the Infrastructure Act 2015, and consulting on a Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy (CWIS). The safety of cyclists and our plans to tackle cyclist fatalities caused by all vehicle types, including HGVs will form a key part of the CWIS document.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-06-17T11:55:24.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348490/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348490/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348490/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-04","Cycling: Accidents","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps, if any, they have taken since 1 May to reduce fatalities to cyclists caused by heavy goods vehicles.","false","Biography information for Earl Attlee",,"Earl Attlee","HL262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348491","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-17","<p>The Department for Transport has not issued guidance on additional equipment fitted to heavy goods vehicles (HGVs), although officials are actively participating in work commissioned by Transport for London (TfL) to develop an independent methodology for performance and evaluation criteria for the effectiveness of such equipment. TfL is aiming for the methodology to be validated and available in the Autumn.</p><p> </p><p>Prior to entry into service, new heavy goods vehicles (HGVs) already require approval of mirrors, including their field of view and correct attachment to the vehicle. Information on these requirements is publicly available.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-06-17T11:56:33.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348491/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348491/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348491/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-04","Cycling: Accidents","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have issued any guidance on performance and evaluation criteria for equipment designed to reduce collisions between heavy goods vehicles and cyclists.","false","Biography information for Earl Attlee",,"Earl Attlee","HL263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348492","Department of Health","false","2015-06-16","<p>Ensuring that the National Health Service is able to support the availability and use of effective medicines for cancer and rare conditions is a key priority for this Government. We continue to work with the pharmaceutical industry on a range of issues, including the pricing of new medicines, through mechanisms such as the Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Cancer Drugs Fund has already helped over 72,000 people and this year £340 million will be provided so people get the drugs they need. A working party made up of NHS England, cancer charities, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence, the Ethical Medicines Industry Group and the Association of the British Pharmaceutical Industry is looking at options for the sustainable long-term commissioning of cancer drugs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We take the issue of ensuring rapid access to innovative therapies very seriously, which is why we have launched an Accelerated Access Review to make recommendations to Government later in the year on speeding up access for NHS patients to innovative and cost effective new medicines, diagnostics and medical technologies.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-06-16T14:39:23.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348492/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348492/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348492/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-04","Drugs: Prices","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the pharmaceutical industry about the costs of new treatments for cancer and rare diseases.","false","Biography information for Lord Turnberg",,"Lord Turnberg","HL264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348493","Department for Education","false","2015-06-09","<p>Department for Education officials meet with representatives of the Church of England and Catholic Church on a regular basis to discuss the impact of Government policy on their schools. They will continue such engagement during the passage of the Education and Adoption Bill.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-06-09T16:20:40.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348493/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348493/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348493/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-04","Church Schools","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Lord Freud on 3 June (HL Deb, col 508), what form the engagement with the church will take, and whether it will take place before the Education and Adoption Bill is introduced.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348494","Department for Education","false","2015-06-09","<p>The government has no plans to review the 50 per cent limit of faith based admissions to free schools and new provision academies.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-06-09T14:23:36.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348494/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348494/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348494/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-04","Faith Schools: Admissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to review the 50 per cent cap on faith-based admissions to free schools.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348495","Department of Health","false","2015-06-15","<p>The Department updated the Charging Regulations on 6 April 2015 to improve the identification and recharging of European Economic Area and non-EEA patients. We will continue to consider whether any additional changes should be made to the charging rules, and communicate as required.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-06-15T11:35:47.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348495/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348495/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348495/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-04","Health Services: Foreign Nationals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to change the rules governing migrants' access to healthcare.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348496","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-18","<p>In the last 12 months there has been an increase of 238,000 disabled people in work. That is really positive, but there is more to do.</p><p> </p><p>We have been very clear that the gap between the employment rates of disabled people and non-disabled people remains too big and have committed to halving it.</p><p> </p><p>Government cannot achieve this ambition alone so we are working closely with disabled people, their organisations, employers and employment support providers to develop our strategy to enable more disabled people to get into, remain in and progress in work.</p><p> </p><p>The Disability Confident Campaign, which actively promotes the Access to Work scheme, is key to supporting employers in working with Government to halve the disability employment gap.</p>",,"Baroness Altmann",,"2015-06-18T11:45:10.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348496/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348496/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348496/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-04","Employment: Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to end the disability employment gap.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348497","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-10","<p /> <p>Details of the policy will be announced in due course. <strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2015-06-10T14:36:17.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348497/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348497/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348497/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-04","Social Security Benefits","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether Personal Independence Payments and Employment Support Allowance will be exempted from the proposed new benefit cap.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348498","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-10","<p>Details of the policy will be announced in due course.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2015-06-10T14:54:37.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348498/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348498/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348498/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-04","Social Security Benefits","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to introduce flexibility into the benefit cap regime to take account of family size and regional housing costs.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348499","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-18","<p>Over £14million has been invested over the last two financial years to support activities aimed at increasing the completeness and accuracy of the register, including in the run up to the General Election. In addition, Electoral Registration Officers have been provided with grant funding in the current financial year of £20million. The Electoral Commission is due to publish its latest analysis of the electoral register later this month, including the impact of activity to promote registration before the election, and it is important to consider any further steps in light of this report.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2015-06-18T16:04:02.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348499/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348499/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348499/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-04","Electoral Register","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the number of people currently not on the electoral register and the reported risk that this will increase with the implementation of individual registration, how much they plan to spend in the current financial year to support local authorities to ensure that the register is as complete as possible.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348500","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-18","<p>The Charter of the Forest was an important document in its own right when it was issued by Henry III in 1217 at the same time as a re-issue of Magna Carta. The Charter re-established rights of access to the forest for free men that had been eroded over the time. However, although the provisions of the Charter of the Forest remained in force for a number of centuries, it has not enjoyed the same lasting and worldwide recognition as Magna Carta, which has had an enduring significance on the development of the concept of the rule of law.</p><p> </p><p>Consequently, while the Government is actively supporting the celebration of the 800 anniversary of Magna Carta this year, it has no plans to mark and celebrate the 800<sup>th</sup> anniversary of the Charter of the Forest.</p>",,"Lord Faulks","HL273","2015-06-18T14:43:57.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348500/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348500/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348500/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-04","Charter of the Forest","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to mark and celebrate the 800th in 2017 anniversary of the granting of the Charter of the Forest.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348501","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-18","<p>The Charter of the Forest was an important document in its own right when it was issued by Henry III in 1217 at the same time as a re-issue of Magna Carta. The Charter re-established rights of access to the forest for free men that had been eroded over the time. However, although the provisions of the Charter of the Forest remained in force for a number of centuries, it has not enjoyed the same lasting and worldwide recognition as Magna Carta, which has had an enduring significance on the development of the concept of the rule of law.</p><p> </p><p>Consequently, while the Government is actively supporting the celebration of the 800 anniversary of Magna Carta this year, it has no plans to mark and celebrate the 800<sup>th</sup> anniversary of the Charter of the Forest.</p>",,"Lord Faulks","HL272","2015-06-18T14:43:57.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348501/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348501/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348501/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-04","Charter of the Forest","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will mark the 800th anniversary in 2017 of the granting of the Charter of the Forest in a similar way to that in which the Magna Carta is being marked this year.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348502","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-16","<p>A public inquiry into Natural England’s proposals to extend the boundaries of the Lake District and Yorkshire Dales National Parks was held in June 2013. The inspector’s report has been submitted to Defra and is now being considered. The Secretary of State will issue her decisions in due course.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-06-16T12:30:50.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348502/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348502/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348502/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-04","National Parks","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the timetable for decisions on the proposals to extend the Lake District and Yorkshire Dales national parks.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348503","Department for Education","false","2015-06-10","<p>It is up to local authorities to decide how to organise and commission services from children’s centres in their areas. They are best placed to understand local needs and the different ways they can be supported locally. Local authorities must demonstrate that they have devised ways to ensure that services continue; what matters is the quality and impact of services, and how local needs are being supported.</p><p> </p><p>We are clear in statutory guidance that there is a presumption against closure, and local authorities have a duty to consult where changes are planned to local children’s centre provision.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-06-10T16:39:58.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348503/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348503/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348503/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-04","Children's Centres","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to prevent any further closures of Sure Start Children’s Centres.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348504","Department for Education","false","2015-06-10","<p>We expect to consult on the extended entitlement for three- and four-year-old children of working parents; and we will consider the role that Sure Start Children’s Centres might play. Further details will be announced in due course.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-06-10T16:41:05.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348504/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348504/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348504/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-04","Children's Centres","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what role Sure Start Children’s Centres will play in the implementation of their policy to double free childcare for working parents of three and four year-olds.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348505","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-10","<p>Government intends to create a £1 billion fund to unlock homes on brownfield land for additional housing, and ensure that brownfield land is used as much as possible for new development.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We are clear that brownfield land that is suitable for housing has a vital role to play in meeting the need for new homes, and ensuring that the Green Belt is protected. The Government is committed to releasing surplus public sector land with capacity for up to 150,000 homes by 2020.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-06-10T11:33:09.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348505/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348505/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348505/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-04","Derelict Land","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they will take to provide the necessary funding to ensure that brownfield land released by government departments for housing purposes can be developed in locations where its development would not otherwise be viable.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348506","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-16","<p>There is no set amount of grant allocated for new affordable housing developments.</p><p>The Homes and Communities Agency assess all applications on a case by case basis, taking into account local circumstances against the criteria set out in the 2015-18 Affordable Homes Programme prospectus. Around 80% of the Affordable Homes Programme in 2011-15 delivered by the Agency outside London was on brownfield land. <br><br>Applications to deliver affordable homes in London are assessed by the Greater London Authority against their published prospectus (The Mayor’s Housing Covenant 2015-18 Programme).</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-06-16T13:49:29.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348506/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348506/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348506/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-04","Derelict Land","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the case for increasing the percentage of social housing grant for new developments by housing associations on brownfield sites on which the development would not otherwise be financially viable.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348507","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-18","<p>The Government wishes to ensure that brownfield land is prioritised and used as much as possible for new development. We will require local authorities to have a register of suitable brownfield sites and ensure 90 per cent of suitable sites have planning permission for housing by 2020. Our planning guidance stresses the importance of bringing brownfield land back into use and encourages councils to use other local plan policies to promote the viability of brownfield across the local area.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-06-18T11:42:08.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348507/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348507/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348507/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-04","Derelict Land","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what flexibility the National Planning Policy Framework gives to local authorities to prioritise the development of brownfield sites over greenfield land in local plans; and whether they propose to amend the National Planning Policy Framework in order to allow local authorities to strengthen such local policies.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348508","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-17","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the Written Ministerial Statement of 24 March 2015 made by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs (James Duddridge), which I repeated the same day in the House of Lords, (HLWS440).</p><p>Further work building on the independent KPMG Feasibility Study is now underway to seek to clarify fundamental uncertainties around the likely costs, ongoing liabilities and potential demand for resettlement. This is being led by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office in close collaboration with the Ministry of Defence and the Department for International Development, and we will explain our conclusions to interested parties in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-06-17T13:18:01.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348508/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348508/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348508/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-04","Ilois: Resettlement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking on the possible resettlement of the Chagos Islands; which departments are conducting this work; and whether they will publish any further conclusions they reach on the feasibility and costs of resettlement by those exiles and their descendants who wish to return.","false","Biography information for Lord Avebury",,"Lord Avebury","HL280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348509","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-15","<p>This case against Zainab Al Khawaja follows an incident in Jau prison when her father, Abdulhadi Al Khawaja, was on hunger strike. We understand Ms Al Khawaja attempted to enter an area of the prison closed to the public and stage a sit-in, and as a result, was forcibly removed from the facility. She has the right to appeal. Our Embassy in Bahrain will continue to monitor the case closely.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-06-15T11:37:43.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348509/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348509/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348509/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-04","Bahrain: Prisoners","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the arrest and imprisonment of Ms Zainab Al Khawaja whilst attempting to visit her father in prison in Bahrain; and whether they plan to hold discussions with the government of Bahrain about her imprisonment.","false","Biography information for Lord Avebury",,"Lord Avebury","HL281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348510","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-17","<p>The exact numbers of newly displaced and malnourished people following the May outbreak of fighting in Unity State have yet to be confirmed by the United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs. Due to the ongoing fighting, humanitarian access has been extremely limited, preventing assessment of the humanitarian impact. We expect an update in mid-June, following the launch of the mid-year review of the 2015 United Nations Humanitarian Response Plan in Geneva on 16<sup>th</sup> June 2015.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-06-17T16:11:47.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348510/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348510/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348510/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-04","South Sudan: Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of how many newly displaced and malnourished people there are in South Sudan following the latest outbreak of fighting in Unity State.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Sandwich",,"The Earl of Sandwich","HL282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348511","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-17","<p>Since December 2013 over 2 million people have been displaced by the conflict in South Sudan with the majority now residing in refugee camps and reliant on humanitarian aid. While it is too early for assessments for crop production in 2015, widespread disruption to agriculture is predicted to continue across the country and internally displaced people will continue to be reliant on aid, particularly during the dry season.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Under the Humanitarian Response Plan, the United Nations has appealed for USD 1.7 billion for 2015. The UK is one of the top three donors to this plan.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-06-17T16:14:27.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348511/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348511/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348511/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-04","South Sudan: Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the loss of food production this year owing to the conflict in South Sudan; and how they are assisting United Nations agencies and non-governmental organisations to meet the food shortages in the affected areas.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Sandwich",,"The Earl of Sandwich","HL283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348512","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-17","We regularly engage with both parties to the conflict to press them to end the conflict and secure peace. Most recently the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my hon. Friend the Member for Rochford and Southend East (James Duddridge), wrote to the South Sudanese Foreign Minister on 8 June calling on the Government of South Sudan to end the fighting and re-engage in peace talks. The failure of the parties to reach agreement in previous peace talks emphasises the need for consistent and united international pressure. We are in discussions with our partners on how the recently created UN sanctions mechanism can be best be used to force the parties to return to negotiations.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-06-17T16:40:56.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348512/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348512/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348512/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-04","South Sudan: Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking, if any, to bring the parties to the conflict in South Sudan together; and what lessons have been learned from previous failures.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Sandwich",,"The Earl of Sandwich","HL284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348513","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-17","<p>The majority of the External Assistance Budget of the European Commission is deemed to be official development assistance eligible, and therefore is included in the calculation of the 0.7 per cent of gross national income.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-06-17T11:53:51.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348513/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348513/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348513/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-04","Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether part of the United Kingdom's net contribution to the European Union development aid budget should be counted in the calculation of the target of 0.7 per cent of gross national product for overseas aid.","false","Biography information for Lord Vinson",,"Lord Vinson","HL285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348514","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-15","<p>In 2013, the Prime Minister secured the first ever cut to the seven-year EU Budget Multiannual Financial Framework (MFF). As a result, according to the Office for Budget Responsibility’s (OBR’s) latest forecast, UK net contributions to the EU Budget going forward will, on average, be lower per year than in 2013/14 – the final year of the last seven-year deal secured by the previous Government – not higher. The Government supports the objectives of the European Structural and Investment Funds. These programmes are now more strongly focused on results following the implementation of a rigorous performance framework sought by the UK and other net payers during MFF negotiations. The Government is committed to continue to ensure maximum restraint and maximum value for money when it comes to EU expenditure.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-06-15T11:41:17.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348514/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348514/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348514/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-04","EU Grants and Loans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the value for money obtained by the European Structural and Investment Funds in the light of the increase in the United Kingdom's net contribution to the European Union budget.","false","Biography information for Lord Vinson",,"Lord Vinson","HL286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348515","Department for Education","false","2015-06-10","<p>It is up to local authorities to decide how to organise and commission services from children’s centres in their areas. They are best placed to understand local needs and the different ways they can be supported locally. Local authorities must demonstrate that they have devised ways to ensure that services continue; what matters is the quality and impact of services, and how local needs are being supported.</p><p> </p><p>We are clear in statutory guidance that there is a presumption against closure, and local authorities have a duty to consult where changes are planned to local children’s centre provision.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-06-10T13:19:23.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348515/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348515/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348515/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-04","Children's Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make it her policy to maintain the number of sure start centres in England.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","1236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348516","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Cabinet Office intends to deliver £17.4m savings through a reduction in programme budgets across the Department, and a range of efficiencies affecting administrative expenditure, reduced use of consultants and contractors, and estates efficiencies.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-06-09T15:00:13.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348516/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348516/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348516/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-04","Cabinet Office: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the breakdown is of the £17 million savings to his Department's budget.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","1251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348517","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Parliamentary Voting System and Constituencies (PVSC) Act 2011 provides for the number of constituencies to be reduced from 650 to 600 and the Government remains committed to equalising the size of constituencies in order to make votes of more equal value. The Government will outline its plans for constituency boundaries when it responds to the Political and Constitutional Reform Committee’s report, <em>What next on the redrawing of parliamentary constituency boundaries?</em>, in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Boundary Commissions are due to commence work on their next reviews of Parliamentary constituencies in spring 2016 in order to submit final reports by 1 October 2018. If approved, the new constituencies would take effect at the next General Election.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","1252","2015-06-09T15:33:07.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348517/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348517/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348517/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-04","Constituencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 3 June 2015 to Question 263, whether it remains his policy to reduce the number of parliamentary constituencies from 650 to 600.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","1274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348518","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Parliamentary Voting System and Constituencies (PVSC) Act 2011 provides for the number of constituencies to be reduced from 650 to 600 and the Government remains committed to equalising the size of constituencies in order to make votes of more equal value. The Government will outline its plans for constituency boundaries when it responds to the Political and Constitutional Reform Committee’s report, <em>What next on the redrawing of parliamentary constituency boundaries?</em>, in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Boundary Commissions are due to commence work on their next reviews of Parliamentary constituencies in spring 2016 in order to submit final reports by 1 October 2018. If approved, the new constituencies would take effect at the next General Election.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","1274","2015-06-09T15:33:07.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348518/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348518/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348518/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-04","Constituencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when he plans to enact the reduction in the number of seats in this House from 650 to 600.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","1252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348519","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-09","<p>The introduction of Individual Electoral Registration has made it easier than ever before for electors to register to vote through online registration.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Electoral Commission will be publishing a report this month on the electoral registers used for the General Election, providing the most up to date picture about registration levels.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2015-06-09T15:30:41.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348519/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348519/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348519/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-04","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of changes to the number of people on the electoral register since the introduction of individual electoral registration; and what changes there have been to the age and demographic profiles of electors in that period.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","1250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348520","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-12","<p>The early warning notices brought in by the Anti-social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014 came into force in October 2014 and it is too early to make an assessment of their effectiveness. However, the table attached shows the number of successful prosecutions brought under the Dangerous Dogs Act 1991 for allowing a dog to be dangerously out of control in 2014. The period for June to December covers the period when the amendments to the 1991 Act by the Anti-social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014 came into force.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>Table 1</strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Defendants proceeded against at magistrates courts and found guilty at all courts of offences under selected sections of the Dangerous Dogs Act 1991, England, 2014 <sup>(1)(2)</sup></strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Legislation</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Outcome</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>January </strong></p><p><strong>To</strong></p><p><strong>May</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>June</strong></p><p><strong>To</strong></p><p><strong>December</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Section 3(1) Dangerous Dogs Act 1991</p></td><td><p>Proceeded</p><p>Against</p><p>Found</p><p>Guilty</p></td><td><p>444</p><p> </p><p>325</p></td><td><p>718</p><p> </p><p>553</p></td><td><p>1,163</p><p> </p><p>878</p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Section 3 Dangerous Dogs Act 1991</p></td><td><p>Proceeded</p><p>Against</p><p>Found</p><p>Guilty</p></td><td><p><strong>-</strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>-</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3</strong></p><p> </p><p>2</p></td><td><p>3</p><p> </p><p>2</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>(1) The figures given in the table relate to persons for whom these offences were the principal offences for which they were dealt with. When a defendant has been found guilty of two or more offences it is the offence for which the heaviest penalty is imposed. Where the same disposal is imposed for two or more offences, the offence selected is the offence for which the statutory maximum penalty is the most severe.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>(2) Every effort is made to ensure that the figures presented are accurate and complete. However, it is important to note that these data have been extracted from large administrative data systems generated by the courts and police forces. As a consequence, care should be taken to ensure data collection processes and their inevitable limitations are taken into account when those data are used.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Source: Justice Statistics Analytical Services - Ministry of Justice. Ref: 271-15 PQC 1009 - 1010 &amp; 1013</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-12T13:40:59.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348520/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348520/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348520/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-04","Dangerous Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effect of the changes to the law concerning dog control made in the Anti-social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","1163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348521","Department of Health","false","2015-06-10","<p>Details of meetings held by Ministers and Permanent Secretaries with external organisations are published quarterly and can be found at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministerial-gifts-hospitality-overseas-travel-and-meetings" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministerial-gifts-hospitality-overseas-travel-and-meetings</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information requested in respect of other officials’ meetings is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-10T16:17:52.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348521/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348521/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348521/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-04","Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with which organisations his Department has discussed the responsibility deal since December 2014.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","1115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348522","Department of Health","false","2015-06-11","<p>Incentivising general practitioners through the Quality and Outcomes Framework to ensure patients receive the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) care processes will increase the number of annual foot checks delivered so that patients at risk will be picked up earlier. The latest data published in the National Diabetes Audit report shows that over 85% of all those with diabetes in England and Wales received a foot examination in 2012-13. However, there is still room for improvement.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has launched the National Diabetes Footcare Audit (a new module to be incorporated into the National Diabetes Audit) which will enable all diabetes foot care services to measure their performance against NICE clinical guidelines and peer units.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>According to the National Diabetes Inpatient Audit, in 2011, 58.3% of trusts had a multidisciplinary foot team, and in 2013, 71.8% of trusts had one.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","1117","2015-06-11T10:39:55.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348522/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348522/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348522/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-04","Diabetes: Podiatry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps health authorities are taking to ensure diabetics receive annual checks on their feet.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","1116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348523","Department of Health","false","2015-06-11","<p>Incentivising general practitioners through the Quality and Outcomes Framework to ensure patients receive the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) care processes will increase the number of annual foot checks delivered so that patients at risk will be picked up earlier. The latest data published in the National Diabetes Audit report shows that over 85% of all those with diabetes in England and Wales received a foot examination in 2012-13. However, there is still room for improvement.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has launched the National Diabetes Footcare Audit (a new module to be incorporated into the National Diabetes Audit) which will enable all diabetes foot care services to measure their performance against NICE clinical guidelines and peer units.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>According to the National Diabetes Inpatient Audit, in 2011, 58.3% of trusts had a multidisciplinary foot team, and in 2013, 71.8% of trusts had one.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","1116","2015-06-11T10:39:55.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348523/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348523/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348523/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-04","Diabetes: Podiatry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many diabetic foot clinics are in operation in the UK.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","1117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348524","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-10","<p>We remain in close contact with the Government of Saudi Arabia regarding Yemen. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), discussed it with his Saudi Arabian counterpart on 2 June. He emphasised the importance of moving towards a political process in Yemen and sustained humanitarian access. I also discussed the situation with the Saudi Arabian Foreign Minister in the margins of the EU-GCC Summit on 24 May.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-06-10T12:16:36.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348524/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348524/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348524/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-04","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions his Department has had with the Saudi Arabian government about the conflict in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","1118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348525","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-06-09","<p>I have discussed the operations of Cerberus on a number of occasions including with Government and Executive Ministers.</p><p>It is important that Cerberus lives up to its commitment to be a good partner for Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2015-06-09T10:04:14.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348525/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348525/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348525/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-06-04","Cerberus Capital Management: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment she has made of the operations of the Cerebrus investment fund in Northern Ireland since April 2014.","false","Biography information for Dr Alasdair McDonnell","Belfast South","Dr Alasdair McDonnell","1133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348526","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-09","<p>Many businesses rely on funding and advice from creditors such as Private Equity funds for restructuring purposes, and have used this support to strengthen their business. However, it is inevitable that some businesses cannot overcome their financial difficulties. It is right that those who invest in businesses are allowed compensation in the event the company defaults on their debt.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, the government understands the importance of protecting businesses from unfair or predatory practices by creditors. Anti-asset stripping measures were introduced under the Alternative Investment Fund Managers Directive (AIFMD), which includes specific measures to address concerns about predatory creditors.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-09T16:37:09.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348526/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348526/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348526/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-04","Business: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to protect viable businesses from distressed securities funds.","false","Biography information for Dr Alasdair McDonnell","Belfast South","Dr Alasdair McDonnell","1221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348527","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-09","<p>I refer the hon. Friend to the answer I gave in the House on 8 June 2015 to the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland (Bridget Phillipson).</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-06-09T15:29:56.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348527/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348527/answer","VJ Day.doc  HOC  1253 Monday 8 June 2015.doc","Hansard Extract Monday 8 June 2015","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348527/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-04","VJ Day","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans there are for commemoration and celebration by the armed forces of the 70th Anniversary of VJ Day.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","1253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348528","Department of Health","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Department’s National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) has invited researchers to apply for mesothelioma research funding, in particular to address the research questions identified through the Mesothelioma Priority Setting Partnership and published in December 2014. Eight NIHR programmes are participating in this themed call. Four funding applications for research specifically in mesothelioma are currently under review. The call under the Health Technology Assessment programme closes on 3 September 2015.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-06-09T13:00:37.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348528/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348528/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348528/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-04","Mesothelioma: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of the finance for research into mesothelioma; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","1216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348529","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-09","<p>I am proud of the leadership role that the UK has played on tackling violence against women and children worldwide, and it will continue to be a key priority for my Department. We have increased programmes that tackle violence against women and girls by 63% in the past two years, and now support 103 programmes in 29 countries.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-06-09T15:41:55.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348529/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348529/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348529/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-04","Developing Countries: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what aid she is providing to help countries end violence against women and children as part of new country operational plans; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","1217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348530","Home Office","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Government announced at the Budget on 18 March 2015, that we will allow widows, widowers and surviving civil partners of police officers who have died on duty to keep their survivor’s benefits if they remarry, form a civil partnership or cohabit. This will not apply to all survivors in the 1987 Police Pension Scheme. The Home Office will consult the Police Advisory Board for England and Wales shortly on proposals to implement this change.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-06-09T13:32:08.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348530/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348530/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348530/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-04","Police: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it her policy to allow widows and widowers of police officers who died as serving officers to keep their full pension entitlements when remarrying; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","1218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348531","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-09","<p>Entry and exit from Gaza is difficult and can, at times, be impossible. Entry is through either Israel, with permission from the Israeli authorities, or Egypt, with permission from the Egyptian authorities (although this border has been closed almost entirely since October 2014). Members and Peers should be aware that at this time the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) advises against all travel to Gaza. We do not make representations on behalf of British Nationals, including parliamentarians, wishing to travel.</p><p>The Government has repeatedly made clear to the Chinese and Hong Kong Governments that the decision to refuse to allow the members of the previous Foreign Affairs Committee to enter Hong Kong in December 2014 was wholly unjustified and counter-productive. The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Office, my right hon. Friend the Member for East Devon (Mr Swire) visited Hong Kong on 8 January and met the President of the Legislative Council and a wide range of legislators, which was particularly important given their key role in the constitutional reform process. In addition, FCO officials have regular contacts with the Hong Kong Government. It is the Government’s assessment that British Parliamentarians can visit Hong Kong.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-06-09T14:09:58.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348531/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348531/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348531/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-04","Gaza and Hong Kong: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of whether hon. Members and Peers will be allowed to visit (a) Gaza and (b) Hong Kong; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","1219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348532","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Consumer Rights Act 2015, contains provisions for an independent statutory review of the consumer protection measures in the secondary ticketing market. It will be independently led and it will be presented to Parliament within a year of commencement.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-06-09T10:16:00.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348532/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348532/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348532/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-04","Tickets: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment he has made of the fairness of the operation of the secondary ticketing market; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","1220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348533","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-10","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), has received no recent representations from the Welsh Government about votes at 16 and 17 in the proposed EU referendum.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-06-10T13:55:50.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348533/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348533/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348533/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-04","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has received from the Welsh Government about votes at 16 and 17 in the proposed EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","1232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348534","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-10","<p>The former Home Office Minister of State for Crime Prevention and DFID Parliamentary Under Secretary of State raised restrictions on humanitarian access in Rakhine during her visit in January 2015. I raised this issue repeatedly during my visit in August 2014, I raised it again with the Immigration and Population Minister and Rakhine Chief Minister when they visited London in October 2014. DFID’s Director General for Country Programmes was in Burma 2- 4 June 2015. She visited Rakhine and Naypyidaw and raised the issue of restrictions on humanitarian access with the state authorities in Rakhine, and with senior Ministers of the central Government in Naypyidaw.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-06-10T13:27:19.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348534/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348534/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348534/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-04","Burma: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with which ministers and officials of the Burmese government she has spoken to about restrictions on humanitarian access in Rakhine State in the last six months.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","1174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348535","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-10","<p>DFID is providing no financial assistance directly to the government of Burma. Indirect financial assistance happens in two projects. DFID supports a World Bank trust fund to assist the Government’s Public Financial Management (PFM) modernisation programme. Part of the fund is transferred into designated accounts which the Government and Parliament can use to procure goods and services to support the PFM modernisation programme. Use of the money must be approved by the World Bank and must follow World Bank procurement guidelines. DFID also supports the 3MDG health trust fund which uses some of its funds in support of the Government’s national health programmes, but without actual transfer to government bank accounts.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-06-10T11:38:53.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348535/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348535/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348535/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-04","Burma: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what financial assistance her Department is providing (a) directly and (b) indirectly to the government of Burma.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","1175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348536","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-09","<p /> <p>The First-tier Tribunal - Social Security and Child Support, administered by HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service hears appeals against Department for Work and Pensions’ (DWP) decisions on a range of benefits.</p><p> </p><p>The Tribunal heard the appeal brought by Ms Ely on 27 April. A request for a full statement of reasons was received from the DWP on 15 May.</p><p> </p><p>The Tribunal’s Procedure Rules require the statement of reasons to be provided within one month of the request or as soon as practicable thereafter.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-06-09T16:22:00.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348536/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348536/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348536/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-04","HM Courts and Tribunals Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he expects HM Courts and Tribunals Service to send to the Department for Work and Pensions the Statement of Reasons in respect of the recent appeal, Ref: SC133/14/00156, relating to Ms C Ely; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Simon Burns","Chelmsford","Mr Simon Burns","1254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348537","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Government has made no such assessment.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","1211","2015-06-09T14:06:55.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348537/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348537/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348537/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-04","Landlords: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the total annual contribution in taxes arising from residential landlords which are unincorporated.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","1209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348538","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-09","<p>According to the latest figures published by the Department for Communities and Local Government, the private rental sector accounts for 19% of housing in the UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These properties make an important contribution in balancing the wider housing market, which requires a mix of tenures in order to operate effectively. The provision of rented accommodation also supports the economy through improved labour market flexibility.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-06-09T14:08:58.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348538/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348538/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348538/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-04","Landlords: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the contribution that private-sector residential landlords make to the economy.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","1210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348539","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Government has made no such assessment.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","1209","2015-06-09T14:06:56.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348539/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348539/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348539/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-04","Landlords: Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the total annual contribution in corporation tax paid by residential landlords in the UK.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","1211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348540","Home Office","false","2015-06-09","<p>The information requested is given in the table below. The latest Home Office immigration statistics, on grants of British citizenship by previous nationality, are published in Immigration Statistics January to March 2015, table cz_06 (Citizenship tables), which is available from the Department’s website at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release</a></p><p>A copy will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-06-09T11:53:49.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348540/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348540/answer","PQ 1171 Table.xlsx","Grants of British citizenship","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348540/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-04","EU Nationals: British Nationality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many EU citizens from each EU member state have taken British citizenship in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","1171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348541","Home Office","false","2015-06-09","<p>EU nationals who wish to become British citizens must apply for naturalisation under the British Nationality Act 1981. They are required to meet the same requirements as all other foreign nationals. This includes requirements to have sufficient knowledge of language and life in the United Kingdom -as measured by the &quot;Life in the UK&quot; test which we reformed in the last Parliament- and be of good character. The residential requirements are based on a period of lawful residence in the United Kingdom: 3 years for spouses and civil partners of British citizens and 5 years for others, without excess absences. A person must also be free of immigration time restrictions in the UK, and must have been free of those restrictions for at least 12 months before applying if not the spouse or civil partner of a British citizen. An EEA national becomes free of immigration time restrictions after five years' residence in the United Kingdom in accordance with EEA Regulations.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-06-09T11:52:48.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348541/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348541/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348541/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-04","EU Nationals: British Nationality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the qualifying requirements are for an EU citizen to take British citizenship.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","1172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348542","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-16","<p>The European Commission does not provide staffing numbers by nationality broken down between permanent and temporary agents. In total the numbers of UK nationals employed by the European Commission for each of the last ten years is as follows:</p><p>October 2005: 1453</p><p>April 2006: 1449</p><p>April 2007: 1410</p><p>April 2008: 1360</p><p>April 2009: 1337</p><p>April 2010: 1284</p><p>April 2011: 1162</p><p>April 2012: 1134</p><p>April 2013: 1079</p><p>April 2014: 1053</p><p>The latest figure available is for April 2015 and is 1008.</p><p>In relation to its share of the EU population, the UK has, for many years, been under-represented among the staff of the major EU institutions. In recent years the numbers have decreased as some British officials who were recruited when the UK joined the EEC have retired.</p><p>Increasing the number of British officials is a priority for the Government. The EU Staffing Unit, established in April 2013, is working to promote EU careers across the UK and support candidates with their application. In the short term, the Unit has increased secondments in positions of strategic importance to the UK. The European Fast Stream within the Civil Service has also been re-launched.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2015-06-16T09:07:43.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348542/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348542/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348542/answer","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348542/answer/previousversion/3457","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-04","European Commission: British Nationality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many UK nationals were (a) permanent officials and (b) temporary agents on the staff of the European Commission (i) in each of the last 10 years and (ii) on the latest date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","1205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348543","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-16","<p>The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) will lead the negotiations with the Chancellor of the Exchequer, my right hon. Friend the Member for Tatton (Mr Osborne), myself, and the Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Aylesbury (Mr Lidington) all playing an important role. Departments, including the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, are staffing this appropriately. It is not possible to identify full time equivalent staff numbers because of the wide range of staff who are contributing on an ad-hoc basis.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2015-06-16T09:11:20.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348543/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348543/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348543/answer","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348543/answer/previousversion/3458","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-04","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many full-time equivalent staff in his Department are currently working on renegotiating the UK's relationship with the EU.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","1206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348544","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-16","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) has provided details of staffing at posts, including in Brussels, in the Annual Accounts and Reports for 2012/13 and 2013/2014. The latter can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/foreign-and-commonwealth-office-annual-report-and-accounts-2013-14--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/foreign-and-commonwealth-office-annual-report-and-accounts-2013-14--2</a>. The FCO Annual Accounts and Reports for 2014/2015 will be published later this year.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2015-06-16T09:14:15.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348544/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348544/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348544/answer","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348544/answer/previousversion/3459","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-04","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many full-time equivalent staff were employed at the UK Permanent Representation to the EU (a) in each of the last 10 years and (b) on the latest date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","1207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348545","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-09","<p>The use of best and most versatile farmland is for local planning authorities to lead through their Local Plans. This enables local communities to be consulted and to decide where development should go, and what local food-growing opportunities should be taken forward.</p><p> </p><p>The National Planning Policy Framework sets out the importance for local planning authorities of taking account of the benefits of the best and most versatile farmland in preparing their Local Plans, including consideration of access to affordable, sustainable and healthy food.</p><p> </p><p>Local planning authorities must consult Natural England before permitting non-agricultural development on significant areas of such land if this is outside the Local Plan.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","1136 ; 1137","2015-06-09T15:31:21.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348545/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348545/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348545/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-04","Agriculture: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will bring forward plans to strengthen the protection of best and most versatile agricultural land in national planning policy.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","1135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348546","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-09","<p>The use of best and most versatile farmland is for local planning authorities to lead through their Local Plans. This enables local communities to be consulted and to decide where development should go, and what local food-growing opportunities should be taken forward.</p><p> </p><p>The National Planning Policy Framework sets out the importance for local planning authorities of taking account of the benefits of the best and most versatile farmland in preparing their Local Plans, including consideration of access to affordable, sustainable and healthy food.</p><p> </p><p>Local planning authorities must consult Natural England before permitting non-agricultural development on significant areas of such land if this is outside the Local Plan.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","1135 ; 1137","2015-06-09T15:31:21.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348546/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348546/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348546/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-04","Agriculture: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to strengthen policies relating to food-growing in the National Planning Policy Framework to identify the importance of local food-growing opportunities and the affordability of, and access to, suitable land and associated housing for food-growing.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","1136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348547","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-09","<p>The use of best and most versatile farmland is for local planning authorities to lead through their Local Plans. This enables local communities to be consulted and to decide where development should go, and what local food-growing opportunities should be taken forward.</p><p> </p><p>The National Planning Policy Framework sets out the importance for local planning authorities of taking account of the benefits of the best and most versatile farmland in preparing their Local Plans, including consideration of access to affordable, sustainable and healthy food.</p><p> </p><p>Local planning authorities must consult Natural England before permitting non-agricultural development on significant areas of such land if this is outside the Local Plan.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","1135 ; 1136","2015-06-09T15:31:21.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348547/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348547/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348547/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-04","Soil","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will instruct officials in his Department to discuss with their counterparts in the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs the feasibility of monitoring the loss to development of best and most versatile soil.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","1137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348548","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-09","<p>Defra has recommended that the scope of the EU Timber Regulation is increased to cover a wider range of timber and timber products. This is as part of the current EU-wide review of the Regulation.</p><p>In addition, Defra is actively encouraging better implementation of the EU Timber Regulation across the EU. This includes hosting meetings with EU Timber Regulation enforcement officials from other EU Member States to share practical advice and discuss best practice.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-09T08:31:49.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348548/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348548/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348548/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-04","Timber: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to reach common agreement with other EU member states on amending the EU Timber Regulation so it covers all timber and timber products.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","1138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348549","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-09","<p>Consultation on the programme of measures to implement the Marine Strategy Framework Directive ended on 24 April this year. The consultation document is available at: <a href="https://consult.defra.gov.uk/marine/msfd-programme-of-measures" target="_blank">https://consult.defra.gov.uk/marine/msfd-programme-of-measures</a>.</p><p>We are currently assessing the responses to the consultation and a decision on the final programme of measures will be taken in the autumn.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-09T09:31:25.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348549/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348549/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348549/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-04","Seas and Oceans: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what measures her Department plans to implement to meet the requirements of the Marine Strategy Framework Directive.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","1257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348551","Department of Health","false","2015-06-11","<p>Local clinical commissioning groups, and the NHS Trust Development Authority, are working with the management of the Whittington Hospital to improve financial performance and to ensure that access and waiting times standards are met. Ministers have had no discussions with the management of the Whittington Hospital about its performance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department has made a loan facility of £23.9 million available to Whittington Health Trust. This funding will provide cover for the deficit until such time that the NHS Trust Development Authority is able to make further representations for funding on behalf of the Trust.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","1103 ; 1104","2015-06-11T14:28:10.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348551/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348551/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348551/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-04","Accident and Emergency Departments: Hornsey and Wood Green","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to improve A&E provision in Hornsey and Wood Green constituency.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","1102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348552","Department of Health","false","2015-06-11","<p>Local clinical commissioning groups, and the NHS Trust Development Authority, are working with the management of the Whittington Hospital to improve financial performance and to ensure that access and waiting times standards are met. Ministers have had no discussions with the management of the Whittington Hospital about its performance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department has made a loan facility of £23.9 million available to Whittington Health Trust. This funding will provide cover for the deficit until such time that the NHS Trust Development Authority is able to make further representations for funding on behalf of the Trust.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","1102 ; 1104","2015-06-11T14:28:10.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348552/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348552/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348552/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-04","Whittington Hospital: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent discussions he has had with the management of the Whittington Hospital on that hospital's performance; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","1103"
