"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348340","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-09","<p>Our focus remains on ensuring that the Basic Payment Scheme claimants are able to submit their claims by the deadline, indeed as of 8 June 2015 the RPA have received 58,836 completed claims, which is in line with the number of claims received in previous years.</p><p>In order to help farmers to be able to submit their claims by the deadline the Rural Payments Agency has 50 drop in centres open, 10 mobile support units in operation and a dedicated helpline. The deadline for claim submission is fixed by the regulation, although in recognition of the additional complexity the EU has already extended the deadline to the 15 June. Farmers and agents have received all the information and forms they need to submit claims. Support to farmers will still be available during the late claim period which runs to 10 July where applications can still be received but will incur a penalty.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","1034 ; 1036","2015-06-09T10:07:59.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348340/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348340/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348340/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-03","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans her Department has to help farmers who do not meet the deadline for applications to the Basic Payment Scheme.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","1035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348341","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-09","<p>Our focus remains on ensuring that the Basic Payment Scheme claimants are able to submit their claims by the deadline, indeed as of 8 June 2015 the RPA have received 58,836 completed claims, which is in line with the number of claims received in previous years.</p><p>In order to help farmers to be able to submit their claims by the deadline the Rural Payments Agency has 50 drop in centres open, 10 mobile support units in operation and a dedicated helpline. The deadline for claim submission is fixed by the regulation, although in recognition of the additional complexity the EU has already extended the deadline to the 15 June. Farmers and agents have received all the information and forms they need to submit claims. Support to farmers will still be available during the late claim period which runs to 10 July where applications can still be received but will incur a penalty.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","1034 ; 1035","2015-06-09T10:07:59.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348341/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348341/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348341/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-03","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what representations she has received from the farming community about applications to the Basic Payment Scheme.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","1036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348342","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Chief Veterinary Officer has advised that based on the evidence of two annual culls, his view is that the likelihood of suffering in badgers culled by controlled shooting remains comparable with the range of outcomes reported when other culling activities, currently accepted by society, have been assessed, such as deer shooting.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A copy of the Chief Veterinary Officer’s advice is available at</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/bovine-tb-chief-veterinary-officers-advice-on-outcome-of-year-2-of-the-badger-culls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/bovine-tb-chief-veterinary-officers-advice-on-outcome-of-year-2-of-the-badger-culls</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-09T12:20:42.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348342/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348342/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348342/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-03","Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the statement made by the Minister of State for Farming, Food and the Marine Environment to the Western Morning News on 25 May 2015, what the scientific evidential basis is for the statement that there is not a great deal of difference in practical terms between shooting badgers and shooting other wildlife.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","1037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348343","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-09","<p>Start dates have yet to be decided by the two cull companies in Gloucestershire and Somerset.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-09T12:24:22.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348343/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348343/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348343/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-03","Bovine Tuberculosis: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when she plans to start the third phase of badger cull pilots in Somerset and Gloucestershire.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","1038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348344","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-12","<p>The Government is committed to our strategy to make England free of bovine TB, of which culling badgers in areas where the disease is rife is a key element. Options for how to proceed in extending the policy to other areas are still being considered.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-12T13:25:09.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348344/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348344/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348344/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-03","Bovine Tuberculosis: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans she has to extend badger culling to areas outside the pilots in Somerset and Gloucestershire in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","1039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348345","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-09","<p>Since 7 May 2015, Defra has received a variety of representations both for and against repeal of the Hunting Act 2004 from non-government organisations and the public.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-09T10:32:24.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348345/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348345/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348345/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-03","Hunting Act 2004","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what representations she has received supporting repeal of the Hunting Act 2004 since 7 May 2015.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","1040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348346","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Government has said that it will give Parliament the opportunity to repeal the Hunting Act on a free vote, with a government bill in government time.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-09T10:28:14.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348346/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348346/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348346/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-03","Hunting Act 2004","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether she plans to bring forward legislative proposals to repeal the Hunting Act 2004 in this parliamentary Session.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","1041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348347","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-08","<p>The development of the policy is ongoing, and details will be set out in the impact assessment when the Housing Bill is published.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","1021 ; 1050 ; 1078 ; 1090 ; 1162 ; 1269 ; 1270 ; 1271","2015-06-08T15:00:17.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348347/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348347/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348347/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-03","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what impact assessment his Department has made of the proposed expansion of right to buy to housing association properties; and if he will place that assessment in the Library.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","1059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348348","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-08","<p>The Government, as any legal client, is entitled to privacy in its consultation with legal advisers. This is especially the case during the policy formulation process. The Government’s legal analysis surrounding the extension of the right to buy for housing association tenants will be explained when its legislative proposals are brought before the House.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-06-08T13:21:33.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348348/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348348/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348348/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-03","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what legal advice his Department has received about the compulsory sale of housing association properties; and if he will place that advice in the Library.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","1060"
